'''Rosemarie Haag Bletter''' is a German-born American architectural historian, university professor, writer, and lecturer.

==Education==

Bletter was educated at [[Columbia University]], where she received her BS, MA, and PhD. She completed a master’s thesis on the Catalan Modernista architect [[Josep Vilaseca i Casanovas|Josep Vilaseca]] and a doctoral dissertation on the work of [[Bruno Taut]] and [[Paul Scheerbart]].<ref>[http://www.esperdy.net/?p=1671 "Learning from Bletter" by Gabrielle Esperdy]</ref>

==Academic career==

Bletter has taught at [[Yale University|Yale]], Columbia, the [[New York University Institute of Fine Arts|Institute of Fine Arts, New York University]], and [[The Graduate Center, CUNY|CUNY Graduate Center]]. She supervised twenty-five doctoral dissertations, among them those of the scholars [[Barry Bergdoll]], Larry Busbea, and Gabrielle Esperdy. An expert on twentieth-century European and American architecture, she was instrumental in the favorable reappraisal of [[Art Deco]] building design during the 1970s, is particularly known for her seminal writings on [[German Expressionism|German Expressionist]] and [[Modernist architecture|Early Modernist]] architecture, as well as for her cultural analysis of the architecture of [[Robert Venturi]] and [[Denise Scott Brown]], and as an early exponent in academia of [[Frank Gehry]]'s work.<ref>[http://www.nybooks.com/contributors/rosemarie-haag-bletter/ Rosemarie Haag Bletter page at ''The New York Review of Books'']</ref>

==Curatorial==

Bletter was an organizer of the 1975 [[Brooklyn Museum]] exhibition "Skyscraper Style" (co-sponsored by the [[Architectural League of New York]]). It was based on her book of the same name (with the photographer Cervin Robinson), one of the first serious studies to validate American Art Deco commercial architecture.<ref>[https://www.amazon.com/dp/0195018737/ ''Skyscraper Style: Art Deco New York'']</ref> With [[Martin Filler]], among others, she was a guest curator of the 1985 [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] exhibition "High Styles: Twentieth Century American Design."<ref>[http://www.csmonitor.com/1985/1018/hjwhit.html "Whitney Museum exhibition of 20th-century design highlights an array of modernist trends,"] ''Christian Science Monitor'', October 18, 1985</ref> Bletter and Filler wrote and conducted the interviews for three documentary films produced by Michael Blackwood Productions: ''Beyond Utopia: Changing Attitudes in American Architecture'' (1983), ''Arata Isozaki: Early Work in Japan'' (1985), and ''Stirling'' (1987).<ref>[http://www.michaelblackwoodproductions.com/alpha_index.php Michael Blackwood Productions]</ref> She also served on the advisory panel and as an essayist for the Denver Art Museum’s 2001-2004 traveling exhibition "US Design: 1975-2000."<ref>[https://books.google.com/books/about/US_design_1975_2000.html?id=SEBQAAAAMAAJ US design 1975-2000]</ref>

